ts -- tNurturing a Leadership Cohort for Chinese Faculties of Education -- tSino-Canadian Legal Partnerships in Law and Education: Genesis, Groundwork, and Growth -- tGender and Development in CIDA’s Programs: A Reflection on the Doing of Feminist Collaboration -- tClosing the Circle: Reflections on Past and Future Partnerships across the Disciplines -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada was one of the first Western countries to sign an agreement to provide development aid to China in 1983, and the Canadian International Development Agency invited universities to cooperate in ways that would facilitate "the multiplication of contacts at the thinking level." In Canadian Universities in China’s Transformation, leading scholars from Canadian and Chinese universities elaborate on the historical experience of collaboration in areas as different as environmental science, marine science, engineering, management, law, agriculture, medicine, education, minority cultures, and women’s studies. Contributors use theoretical frames such as dependency theory, human capital, the knowledge economy, and Habermas’s theory of communicative action, to facilitate a striking dialogue between Canadian and Chinese perspectives on common questions. They provide insights into factors that ensured the long-term success of some partnerships, as well as barriers that hindered others, and vivid lessons for current collaboration. Case studies include a project that began with the training of Chinese judges developing into reciprocal programs in legal education in China, Canada, and Latin America, and an examination of how joint environmental research has had policy impacts at national and international levels. Presenting the story of universities working together in the era after the Cultural Revolution, Canadian Universities in China’s Transformation is a unique account of partnerships in knowledge production and application and their resulting impacts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducational exchangeszCanada. 0aEducational exchangeszChina. 0aUniversities and collegesxEconomic aspectszChina. 0aUniversities and collegesxSocial aspectszChina. 0aUniversity cooperationzCanada. 0aUniversity cooperationzChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBeamish, Paul W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBild, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Jing M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChongan, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaiyan, Qiang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayhoe, Christy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayhoe, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsiung, Ping-Chun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuaizu, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiayi, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJie, Ni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLefebvre, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLing, Yao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMirus, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPan, Julia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPan, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigaud, Marie-Claude, econtributor